	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>New submission from Brazil on subsidies</h1>

			
			<h4>
												19 September 2005
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> A submission from Brazil to the WTO defines fisheries subsidies as including ‘all financial contributions or income or price support by a government that are given to or on behalf of fishing interests to all capture fisheries excluding inland fisheries and aquaculture, both inland and marine.’ Brazil also considers that the purchase of foreign access rights, or government-to-government payments to facilitate access for the domestic fishing fleet of one country to the fisheries resources of another are subsidies.</p><p> Brazil further proposes that there should be an exhaustive list of non-actionable (‘green box’) fisheries subsidies, provided that they do not have trade-distorting or production-distorting effects through enhancing capacity and overfishing. Subsidies that do not meet those conditions or do not fall within the exhaustive ‘green box’ list should be considered prohibited subsidies (‘red box’). For LDCs, however, ‘red box’ subsidies would be deemed non-actionable for ten years, during which they could only be challenged if they were trade distorting.</p><p> Brazil advocates that under certain conditions subsidies to small-scale fishing and to artisanal fishing would be non-actionable, provided that such fisheries are not ‘patently at risk’. Thus subsidies for small-scale fishing using vessels of not more than 24 metres and with a total annual catch of not more than 250 tonnes would be non-actionable.</p><p> As regards S&amp;D treatment, Brazil suggested that developing countries that are members of a regional fisheries-management organisation (RFMO) should be allowed to maintain certain capacity-enhancing subsidies as long as the enhancement does not extend beyond the ‘sustainable level of exploitation defined by the limits established under the RFMO’.</p><p> On the same topic, the submission from Fiji, Papua New Guinea and the Solomon Islands, to be discussed in September, advocates that under S&amp;D provisions, all development assistance to developing coastal states, assistance to artisanal or small-scale fisheries, access fees from fishing access agreements, fiscal incentives to facilitate the development of capabilities of small vulnerable coastal states, should not be subject to subsidies disciplines.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p> Brazil’s contribution to the discussion on the framework for disciplines on fisheries subsidies, June 30th 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://docsonline.wto.org/DDFDocuments/t/tn/rl/Gen56.doc" target="_self">http://docsonline.wto.org/DDFDocuments/t/tn/rl/Gen56.doc</a> <br /> </p><p> Submission by Fiji, Papua New Guinea and the Solomon Islands on disciplines on fisheries subsidies, July 5th 2005</p><p>

<a href="http://docsonline.wto.org/DDFDocuments/t/tn/rl/Gen57.doc" target="_self">http://docsonline.wto.org/DDFDocuments/t/tn/rl/Gen57.doc</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> Until recently, the so-called ‘Friends of Fish’ group of countries have called most of the shots in the fisheries subsidies debate at the WTO. The entry of Brazil into the debate, and the recent submission from the three ACP countries, Fiji, Papua New Guinea and the Solomon Islands, are therefore both welcome and timely.</p><p> Although some kinds of subsidies may encourage overcapacity and hasten the process of overfishing, they are not a necessary condition for it. Overfishing results also from deeper-rooted problems, such as ill-defined access rights and the use of inappropriate fishing methods.</p><p> It is vital that this debate focuses more on the many favourable effects that subsidies can create in the fisheries economies of LDCs and developing countries. In this regard, and in addition to defining how S&amp;D treatment should be applied, attention needs to be given to Article 27.1 of the ASCM. This recognises that ‘subsidies may play an important role in the economic development of developing country members’. This would rubber-stamp at least three of the four demands made by Fiji, Papua New Guinea and the Solomon Islands, i.e. that no development assistance to developing coastal states, assistance to artisanal or small-scale fisheries, and fiscal incentives to facilitate the development of capabilities of small vulnerable coastal states should be subject to subsidies disciplines.</p><p> In the case of access fees from fishing-access agreements, whilst recognising the dependency of some small-island developing countries on these revenues, certain conditions need to be applied. First and foremost, vessel owners should pay the full costs of access, otherwise they will be put at an unfair disadvantage with regard to both resource and market access. The financial contribution from the flag states concerned should be towards promoting sustainable development and responsible fisheries.</p>
		</div>
		
		<div class="clear"></div>

		
	</article>

